            {
              "id": "3faed612",
              "elType": "widget",
              "settings": {
                "title": "Improving the challenges of planting Vetiver"
              },
              "elements": [],
              "widgetType": "heading"
            },
            {
              "id": "1b9f3c1b",
              "elType": "widget",
              "settings": {
                "editor": "<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Vetiver is an exceptional plant with features of great interest for bioengineering and phytoremediation applications. When used as a hedgerow placed on level, Vetiver works well against erosion and is then known as the Vetiver System. Somehow, despite it’s great potential, the Vetiver System hasn’t spread as much as it’s needed worldwide. Many reasons could explain this unawareness: lack of funding, insuffisant education and promotion, plant unavailability, unprofitable crop, etc. Still, solutions must be set forth to facilitate access to the Vetiver System and spread its implementation in different parts of the world, including by helping local authorities learn how to apply it to protect their soil, through educational programs for instance.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Very resilient, Vetiver doesn't need much care once established and consequently requires very low human or financial input. Nonetheless, there are valid explanations as to why the implementation of the Vetiver system is not attractive enough for different communities around the world. The main challenge that occurs in the process of the development of the system is during its implantation phase. Indeed, while planting the plant itself is easy, Vetiver needs a fair amount of irrigation in the first stage of its culture to efficiently get started. Yet, it can become difficult to provide the necessary amount of water in remote, poor and water scarce areas of the world.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">One of the main goals of our research is to focus on finding efficient and easy techniques to irrigate Vetiver. If we look at the present practice, most people implement Vetiver during the appropriate season: they wait until they’re sure rain is going to dig out the plants in order to multiply them, and then get all the material ready. Even if proper rain is still the best irrigation method, it has many disadvantages. Indeed, it greatly limits the availability and the possibility to implement the system, pushing it into short seasons. Unfortunately, in many climates precipitations are not easily predictable and it can be difficult to start the entire process if it doesn’t rain. There are also many climates when the rain is too heavy for most periods of the rainy seasons to allow small plants to establish strong roots into the wet soil, if they’re not entirely washed out by the runoff. Unreliable rain makes it difficult for complex logistics to function properly as they need to coordinate many elements, and climate change is likely to make precipitation even more unpredictable.</span></p>",
                "align": "justify",
                "_margin": {
                  "unit": "px",
                  "top": "5",
                  "right": "5",
                  "bottom": "5",
                  "left": "5",
                  "isLinked": true
                },
                "_padding": {
                  "unit": "px",
                  "top": "0",
                  "right": "0",
                  "bottom": "0",
                  "left": "0",
                  "isLinked": true
                }
              },
              "elements": [],
              "widgetType": "text-editor"
            },
