            {
              "id": "fdf51e2",
              "elType": "widget",
              "settings": {
                "editor": "<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Many projects, involving trucks and employees, usually operate different irrigation tools to establish vetiver in the first two weeks of its culture. Some use a drip system, from a tank that they move, but most are irrigating by hand using a watering tank. While it’s still a good solution, few communities have access to a truck that can deliver a water tank as well as a pump and a backhoe long enough to water several dozens meters of hedgerow. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Another reason why it would be very useful to find better ways to irrigate Vetiver is that some of the most important areas to protect from erosion are very difficult to access, especially for vehicles. In fact, in order to properly start restoring a watershed, it would be better to start with the most elevated areas of the watershed, where water accumulates most steering force. Deforested areas are also another important environment where fighting erosion is crucial. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In recent years, various experimental products and innovations have appeared in the irrigation sector. Hydrogel or silica gel, one of these new watering techniques, generates a lot of enthusiasm because of the numerous possibilities it offers. Hydrogel can retain up to 500 times its weight in water and hold it for a period up to several months. When provided with some source of water, it can rehydrate and provide water for a period up to six years. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Spraying water is also quite inefficient because of the loss of water through natural processes, like evaporation, which pushes to irrigate when the sun is not very strong, early in the morning or late in the day. But the most important loss of water occurs through soil infiltration, which is normal, because we don’t want the soil to retain too much water, but causes a great inefficiency in water distribution. Hydrogel offers a great way to provide plants with just the right amount of water they need without losing it in soil infiltration. The amount of water that has to be carried is then greatly reduced, which makes it easier both on the labor force and machinerie.</span></p>",
                "align": "justify"
              },
              "elements": [],
              "widgetType": "text-editor"
            },
